The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, July 12, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, July 11: The government will continue to pay a 9 per cent return on investments in LICs Varishtha Pension Bima Yojana, though the scheme is being wound up. The scheme will be closed but existing investors will continue to get pension at the rate of 9 per cent, a finance ministry official said here today. A new senior citizens savings scheme will be launched soon with similar returns to take care of their needs. It will be a reincarnation of Dada-Dadi Bonds announced by the NDA government in its interim budget.																								 New Delhi, July 11: Bharat Sanchar Nigam Ltd (BSNL) is all set to start full-fledged broadband services by December initially covering 200 cities. Meanwhile, the governments broadband policy will take some more time as telecom regulator Trai will send its final set of replies to the queries raised by the department of telecom tomorrow, said Pradip Baijal, chairman, Trai.																								 New Delhi, July 11: The Centre today assured corporate India that the effective service tax would be only 6 per cent and not 10 per cent as proposed in the budget due to availability of credit on manufacturing.																								 Chennai, July 11: Two US-based private equity funds have bought a 11.74 per cent stake in Coimbatore-based Sakthi Sugars Ltd for a total of Rs 18.21 crore.																								 New Delhi, July 11: Research firm IDC has said as much as 36 per cent of the software installed on computers worldwide in 2003 was pirated and listed emerging markets like India, China and Russia as high-piracy regions.
